plt.figure()  # Create a new figure

plt.title("Drop Tower: Acceleration X vs Time")
plt.xlabel("Time (s)")
plt.ylabel("Acceleration x (m/s^2)")

In[7]:
# Creating sub plots for x and y and z accelerations
fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 1, figsize=(7, 6), sharex=True, sharey=True)

sns.lineplot(x="Time (s)", y="Acceleration x (m/s^2)", data=droptower2,
              color = "green", linestyle="-", label="Acceleration x", ax=ax[0])
sns.lineplot(x="Time (s)", y="Acceleration y (m/s^2)", data=droptower2,
              color = "blue", linestyle="-", label="Acceleration y", ax=ax[1])
sns.lineplot(x="Time (s)", y="Acceleration z (m/s^2)", data=droptower2,
              color = "red", linestyle="-", label="Acceleration z", ax=ax[2])

ax[0].set_title("Drop tower: X and Y and Z Acceleration Plots") # Set title for the first plot
plt.xlabel("Time (s)")
ax[0].set_ylabel("Acceleration (m/s^2)") # Set y-label for the first plot
ax[1].set_ylabel("Acceleration (m/s^2)") # Set y-label for the second plot
ax[2].set_ylabel("Acceleration (m/s^2)") # Set y-label for the third plot

#plt.xlim([0,200])

plt.xlim(50, 170)  # Set x-axis limits to full data range
plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout to prevent overlap
plt.show()
Figure

In[9]:
# Plotting both acceleration x and y and z on the same graph
plt.figure()  # Create a new figure
sns.lineplot(x="Time (s)", y="Acceleration x (m/s^2)", data=silver2, marker="h",
              markersize=5, color = "green", linestyle="--", label="Acceleration x") # Plot the x data
sns.lineplot(x="Time (s)", y="Acceleration y (m/s^2)", data=silver2, marker="d",
              markersize=5, color = "blue", linestyle="-", label="Acceleration y") # Plot the y data
sns.lineplot(x="Time (s)", y="Acceleration z (m/s^2)", data=silver2, marker="*",
              markersize=5, color = "red", linestyle="dotted", label="Acceleration z") # Plot the z data
plt.title("Silver: Acceleration vs Time")
plt.xlabel("Time (s)")
plt.ylabel("Acceleration (m/s^2)")
plt.xlim([250,275])  # Set x-axis limits to full data range
plt.ylim(silver2[["Acceleration x (m/s^2)", "Acceleration y (m/s^2)", "Acceleration z (m/s^2)"]].min().min(),
         silver2[["Acceleration x (m/s^2)", "Acceleration y (m/s^2)", "Acceleration z (m/s^2)"]].max().max())  # Set y-axis limits to full data range
plt.show()
Figure
